In CS-250 we covered the agile process and specific frameworks that work within that process. Agile is amazing when it comes to interpretting user needs and creating solid, actionable requirements for a program.
Users rarely describe solutions. They often describe problems or desired outcomes. It's the team's job to break these up into specific behaviors that can be implemented and tested. User stories assist with this 
process by forcing requirements into a simple, user-centered format. This format ensures the development cycle stays focused on delivering value instead of implementation of random features. In addition to focus, 
user stories also create a natural bridge between non-technical and technical stakeholders. Instead of building abstract systems, the development team builds directly towards user goals.

My approach to developing programs is iterative and incremental. Rather than attempting to build a complete system upfront, I focus on developing small, functional pieces that can be tested and improved over time. 
This reduces complexity, exposes issues early, and allows for continuous refinement. Agile processes support this approach by emphasizing adaptability, communication, and continuous delivery. In future development 
work, I aim to incorporate sprint planning, daily stand-ups, incremental development, sprint reviews, and retrospectives. I also have grown to value pair programming and code reviews because these improve code 
quality and encourage shared understanding amognst the team.

Being a good team member in software development means contributing not just through code, but through communication, accountability, and collaboration. A strong team member communicates clearly and consistently 
with teammates, takes ownership of their work and follows through on commitments, is open to feedback and willing to improve, supports teammates when challenges arise, and prioritizes the success of the team over 
individual recognition. Effective collaboration ensures that knowledge is shared, problems are solved efficiently, and the final product is stronger as a result. In Agile environments, where teamwork is essential, 
these qualities directly impact the success of the project.
